  "prompt": "Can a Greek question mark (;) be used instead of a semicolon (;) in a programming language such as C#, Java or Pascal?",
  "response": "In programming languages like C#, Java, and Pascal, the semicolon (`;`) has a specific syntactical significance. It is generally used to terminate statements. On the other hand, the Greek question mark (`\u037e`), which looks similar but is a different character, is not recognized as a semicolon and will likely result in a syntax error if used in place of a semicolon.\n\nHere\u2019s a summary for each language:\n\n1. **C#**: The semicolon (`;`) is used to end statements. Using the Greek question mark in place of the semicolon will cause a compilation error.\n\n2. **Java**: Similar to C#, Java uses the semicolon to terminate statements. The Greek question mark will not be valid and will result in errors.\n\n3. **Pascal**: In Pascal, the semicolon is also used to separate statements. The Greek question mark will not be recognized and will lead to a syntax error.\n\nIn conclusion, you must use the standard ASCII semicolon (`;`) in C#, Java, and Pascal. Using the Greek question mark (`\u037e`) is not appropriate in these programming contexts.",
